Go to 1:26:36 if you want to skip the eigenvalue and eigenvector computations and go straight into the matrix exponential computation.

The matrix exponential $e^{At}$ can be found using the following formula: $e^{At}=\Phi(t)\Phi^{-1}(0)$ where $\Phi(t)$ is a fundamental matrix combining the 2 linearly independent solutions of A into a single matrix. And $\Phi^{-1}(0)$ is the inverse of the fundamental matrix at 0.

Note: matrix multiplication is not commutative the way scalar multiplication is. So answer choice D is not equivalent to answer choice B (if you do the matrix multiplication for both answers you will end up with a different result). In other words, $\Phi(t)\Phi^{-1}(0)\neq\Phi^{-1}(0)\Phi(t)$

Skip to 1:13:56 to go straight to the matrix exponential calculation. While computing the inverse of the fundamental matrix, I forgot to flip a sign. As such the fundamental matrix inverse at 0 is equal to \[\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{5}&\frac{1}{5}\\\frac{4}{5}&\frac{-1}{5}\end{bmatrix}\] The final matrix exponential is still correct. 

Additionally, depending on your Professor, they may only ask you to set up the matrix exponential rather than computing it as well since the computation for a matrix exponential is quite tedious.

In this question I made a typo in the split laplace transform of the differential equation into $\frac{G(s)}{s^2+3s+2}+\frac{2s+2}{s^2+3s+1}$. It should be $\frac{G(s)}{s^2+3s+2}+\frac{2s+2}{s^2+3s+2}$.

I also mentioned at 2:56:56 that convolutions are not commutative. That is incorrect. They are in fact commutative so the order of your F(s) and G(s) will not make a difference. I just ordered the 2 functions as $F(s)\cdot G(s)$ to match it up with the answer choices.

The correct answer for this question does not look like my answer due to the fact that 2 different numbers were chosen for the second linearly independent solution. However, you can further see that both the numbers that I chose and the numbers in the correct answer are valid as they both satisfy the equation $x_1 + x_2 = -1$. The answer uses -2 and 1 while I use -1 and 0. $-2 + 1 = -1$, and $-1 + 0 = -1.$

Additionally, the reason that these extra steps are necessary to compute 2 linearly independent solutions is because although the 2 vectors computed can be linearly independent on their own, they do not satisfy the expression $x'=Ax$ where $A$ is the given matrix. Attaching $\frac{t^{n-1}}{(n-1)!}$ to the new vector generated in each $x_n(t)$ solution satisfies $x'=Ax$.

TLDR: This problem asks about the qualitative behavior of x(t) after "a long time has passed". From this information we can deduce that the problem is asking how the general solution to the model of this question behaves as ${t\to\infty}$. When $t = 0$, $x(t)=x_c(t)+x_p(t)$. However, when ${t\to\infty}$, $x(t)=x_p(t)$ where $x_p(t)=Acos(\omega t) + Bsin(\omega t)$. If you were to graph this it would look like a sine wave. And since $x(t)=x_p(t)$ when ${t\to\infty}$, $x(t)$ will behave like answer C which is also a sine wave.

In-Depth Explanation:
This problem deals with a damped mass-spring system. As such we can model a differential equation that takes up the form of $mx''+cx'+kx=F_0cos(\omega t)$. This differential equation is an inhomogeneous second order linear differential equation. So the general solution of this differential equation will take up the form of $x(t)=x_c(t)+x_p(t)$ where $x_c(t)$ is the homogeneous complementary portion of the solution and $x_p(t)$ is the inhomogeneous particular portion of the solution. 

Generally speaking, we know that $x_c(t)$ takes up the form of $C_1 e^{\lambda_1 t}+C_2 e^{\lambda_2 t} +...$. Additionally, the inhomogenous portion of the differential equation is $F_0cos(\omega t)$. As such $x_p(t)$ can be found using the method of undetermined coefficients giving us a solution that takes up the form of $Acos(\omega t) + Bsin(\omega t)$. So $x(t)$ would be equal to something taking up the form of $C_1 e^{\lambda_1 t}+C_2 e^{\lambda_2 t} +... + Acos(\omega t) + Bsin(\omega t)$. 

The key takeaway from this is that in order to solve for $C_1$ and $C_2$ we would need to take into account the initial conditions of the problem (assuming this is an IVP). However in order to solve for $A$ and $B$, those terms are not dependent on initial conditions. And we know that $x_p(t)$ takes up the form of $Acos(\omega t) + Bsin(\omega t)$ As such that makes $x_p(t)$ a Steady Periodic Solution.

Since we know that $C_1$ and $C_2$ are dependent on initial conditions we can deduce that the behavior of the solution when $t=0$ is $x(t)=x_c(t)+x_p(t)$. But initial conditions matter less and less as time progresses (keyword being initial). That means that the behavior of $x_c(t)$ becomes more and more insignificant over time. From this we can model a limit of the general solution $\lim_{t\to\infty}x(t)=x_p(t)$. 

We know that $x_p(t)=Acos(\omega t) + Bsin(\omega t)$. If you were to graph this it would take up the form of a sinusoidal wave and the closest matching answer to $x_p(t)=Acos(\omega t) + Bsin(\omega t)$ is answer choice C.

VIDEO CORRECTION:

I made a mistake with the derivatives in this explanation, it should be $-A \cos t$ in the second derivative. I (again accidentally) correct this when solving the system of equations by writing the second line as $[4 \: 2]$ instead of $[6 \: 2]$, getting the correct answer.
Skip to 4:43 to jump straight into the particular solution computation.
I said the answer to this question was $y_p(t)$ again. I meant $y_p(x)$ like every other time I made that mistake in this question LOL.

Note: in the explanation I accidentally wrote $x(t)$ instead of $y(x)$ throughout the computation for the particular solution. Treat each $x(t)$ or $x_p(t)$ term as $y(x)$ and $y_p(x)$.

The particular solution $y_p(x)$ for this inhomogeneous differential equation can be found using the variation of parameters by using the formula \[y_p(x)=-y_1(x)\int\frac{y_2(x)f(x)}{det(W)}dx+y_2(x)\int\frac{y_1(x)f(x)}{det(W)}dx\] Where $f(x)$ is equal to the inhomogenous portion of the differential equation (in this case 2) and $det(W)$ is the determinant of the Wronskian matrix of the given solutions to the homogeneous differential equation (in this case $x^3$). \[\]Plugging the given values in the formula for variation of parameters results in a particular solution of \[y_p(x)=x^2(ln(x))^2\]
A negative sign was missed in the video, $y_p =  -e^{-3t}(1+ln(t))$ is the correct answer.
